{
  "texts": [
    "The first is purely functional-analytic and it is here that we rely on the Hahn-Banach separation theorem.",
    "The second step is proving the following proposition.Proposition 1.5.",
    "For any S > 0, there exists a smooth map ρ 0 ∈ L ∞ (Q) with ∥ρ 0 ∥ ∞ ≤ 2 together with a weak * open set U with ρ 0 ∈ U and such that for every ρ ∈ U, there is no solution (f i, π i) to the equation (1.3) satisfying i max{Lip(f i), ∥f i ∥ ∞ } d j=1 Lip(π j i) ≤ S. (1.5)An important remark is that the reason we require ρ 0 to be smooth is only to be certain that there exists some Lipschitz solution to (1.3) with right hand side ρ 0.Once we obtain a proof of Proposition 1.5, the Hahn-Banach theorem is used to construct a functional separating the set U from the set of L ∞ (Q) maps for which there exists a solution satisfying (1.5).",
    "Due to working with the weak * topology, this separating functional lies in L 1 (Q) and as we increase S → ∞ we obtain the sequence required in the definition of strong Lipschitz non-regularity.The proof of Proposition 1.5 is overall quite similar to the proof, due to Burago and Kleiner [11], that the prescribed Jacobian equation lacks biLipschitz solutions.",
    "Therefore it is also quite similar to the main result concerning the pushforward equation of Dymond at el [22]."
  ]
}